I now have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Let me now compile my comprehensive implementation plan.

---

# Implementation Plan: Enhanced Profile Widget System with Internal Blocks

## Summary of Codebase Analysis

I have thoroughly examined the following files:

- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\ProfilePage\MyProfile.jsx`** (~2040 lines) -- The main profile component containing all widget state, handlers, and JSX rendering
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\ProfilePage\myprofile.css`** (~1160+ lines) -- All widget CSS classes
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\VisitProfile\VisitProfile.jsx`** -- Read-only visitor view of widgets
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\VisitProfile\visitProfile.css`** -- Visitor widget styles
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\index.css`** -- CSS variable system (light/dark themes)
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\services\uploadService.js`** -- Server-side persistence (JSON column `profile_layout`)
- **`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\API\Api.js`** -- Client API calls

---

## 1. Data Model Changes

### Current widget shape (line 67-83 of MyProfile.jsx):
```js
{
    id: 'widget_1234_abc123',
    type: 'note',           // or 'photo_note'
    size: 'md',             // 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg'
    title: 'New widget',
    note: '',
    image_url: '',
    x: 24, y: 24,
    height: null,
    image_width: null,
    image_height: null,
    pinned_section: null
}
```

### New widget shape -- add `blocks` array:
```js
{
    id: 'widget_1234_abc123',
    type: 'note',           // keep for backward compat; ignored when blocks exist
    size: 'md',
    title: 'New widget',    // keep as widget-level title (backward compat)
    note: '',               // keep for backward compat
    image_url: '',           // keep for backward compat
    x: 24, y: 24,
    height: null,
    image_width: null,
    image_height: null,
    pinned_section: null,
    blocks: []              // NEW: array of block objects; empty = legacy mode
}
```

### Block data model:
```js
// Text block
{
    id: 'block_1234_abc123',
    type: 'text',
    content: 'Hello world',
    bg_color: null,         // null = transparent, or '#rrggbb'
    x: 0,
    y: 0,
    width: 160,
    height: 40
}

// Image block (mini-widget with title, note, image, bg color)
{
    id: 'block_1234_def456',
    type: 'image',
    title: 'Photo title',
    note: 'Caption text',
    image_url: 'https://...',
    bg_color: null,
    x: 0,
    y: 60,
    width: 200,
    height: 180,
    image_width: null,
    image_height: null
}
```

### Backward compatibility strategy:
- When `widget.blocks` is undefined/empty, render the widget with the legacy `title`/`note`/`image_url` fields exactly as today
- When `widget.blocks` has items, render the block canvas instead
- The edit panel detects `blocks.length > 0` to show the block-based editor
- Legacy widget type selector is replaced by an "Add block" toolbar when blocks exist
- Migration: When a user first clicks "Convert to blocks" (or "Add block" on a legacy widget), the existing title/note/image_url are automatically converted into blocks

